4. DATA PIPELINE ARCHITECTURE

4.1 Data Acquisition Framework

```
DATA SOURCES BY CATEGORY:

1. MEDICAL LITERATURE (3 Exabytes)
   ├── Sources:
   │   • PubMed Central (35M articles)
   │   • ClinicalTrials.gov (500K trials)
   │   • Medical Textbooks (500K volumes)
   │   • Conference Proceedings (1M+)
   │   • Patent Databases (10M+ patents)
   ├── Processing:
   │   • Quantum NLP for extraction
   │   • Knowledge graph construction
   │   • Evidence grading & validation
   │   • Cross-referencing & linking
   └── Updates: Real-time as published

2. CLINICAL DATA (2 Exabytes)
   ├── Sources:
   │   • Electronic Health Records (500M patients)
   │   • Medical Imaging (1B images)
   │   • Laboratory Results (10B records)
   │   • Pharmacy Data (5B prescriptions)
   │   • Patient Monitoring (Real-time streams)
   ├── Processing:
   │   • De-identification & anonymization
   │   • Standardization (FHIR, SNOMED)
   │   • Quality validation & cleaning
   │   • Longitudinal analysis
   └── Privacy: Federated learning only

3. GENOMIC DATA (2 Exabytes)
   ├── Sources:
   │   • Human Genomes (100M whole genomes)
   │   • Pathogen Genomes (1B sequences)
   │   • Protein Structures (10M structures)
   │   • Epigenetic Data (1B data points)
   │   • Transcriptomic Data (500M samples)
   ├── Processing:
   │   • Sequence alignment & annotation
   │   • Variant calling & interpretation
   │   • Structural biology analysis
   │   • Functional genomics integration
   └── Updates: Daily sequencing data

4. EPIDEMIOLOGICAL DATA (1 Exabyte)
   ├── Sources:
   │   • WHO Surveillance Systems
   │   • National Health Agencies (200+)
   │   • Environmental Sensors (1M+)
   │   • Mobility Data (10B devices)
   │   • Climate & Weather Data
   ├── Processing:
   │   • Real-time stream processing
   │   • Spatiotemporal analysis
   │   • Anomaly detection
   │   • Predictive modeling
   └── Updates: Real-time streams

5. PHARMACEUTICAL DATA (1 Exabyte)
   ├── Sources:
   │   • Drug Databases (100K compounds)
   │   • Clinical Trial Data (500K trials)
   │   • Pharmacovigilance (100M reports)
   │   • Molecular Libraries (10M compounds)
   │   • Drug Interaction Databases
   ├── Processing:
   │   • Molecular property prediction
   │   • ADMET profiling
   │   • Target identification
   │   • Mechanism of action analysis
   └── Updates: Daily from research

6. PUBLIC HEALTH DATA (1 Exabyte)
   ├── Sources:
   │   • Health Policy Documents
   │   • Economic Impact Studies
   │   • Social Determinants Data
   │   • Healthcare System Metrics
   │   • Population Health Surveys
   ├── Processing:
   │   • Policy analysis & impact assessment
   │   • Economic modeling
   │   • Equity analysis
   │   • System performance evaluation
   └── Updates: As published
```

4.2 Data Processing Pipeline

```
PIPELINE ARCHITECTURE:

Ingestion → Processing → Storage → Access
    │           │           │         │
    ▼           ▼           ▼         ▼
┌─────────┐ ┌─────────┐ ┌───────┐ ┌───────┐
│  Data   │ │ Quantum │ │Multi- │ │Feder- │
│Sources  │ │  ETL    │ │Tier   │ │ated   │
│(10K+)   │ │Pipeline │ │Storage│ │Access │
└─────────┘ └─────────┘ └───────┘ └───────┘
    │           │           │         │
    ▼           ▼           ▼         ▼
┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐
│         QUALITY CONTROL GATES           │
│  • Completeness: 99.9%                  │
│  • Accuracy: 99.99%                     │
│  • Timeliness: Real-time                │
│  • Consistency: Cross-validation        │
│  • Privacy: Differential privacy (ε=0.1)│
└─────────────────────────────────────────┘

PROCESSING STEPS:
1. Ingestion:
   • Real-time streaming (Kafka)
   • Batch processing (Spark)
   • API-based collection
   • Manual upload portals

2. Cleaning:
   • Outlier detection
   • Missing data imputation
   • Standardization
   • De-duplication

3. Transformation:
   • Feature engineering
   • Embedding generation
   • Normalization
   • Aggregation

4. Validation:
   • Cross-source validation
   • Expert review
   • Statistical testing
   • Compliance checking

5. Storage:
   • Hot: For active training (Quantum RAM)
   • Warm: For frequent access (NVMe)
   • Cold: For archival (DNA storage)
   • Compliance: Audit trails

6. Access:
   • Federated learning nodes
   • Privacy-preserving queries
   • API endpoints
   • Research portals
```

